'''rammap''' - Template for RAM map tables on games.darkrepos.com

==Description==

This template creates standardized RAM map tables documenting the runtime memory layout of games. It supports different memory regions (zero page, stack, work RAM, VRAM, etc.).

==Usage==

===Basic Usage===
<pre>
{{rammap}}
</pre>

===With Parameters===
<pre>
{{rammap
| platform = NES
| region = Work RAM
| description = Custom description text
}}
</pre>

==Parameters==

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Parameter !! Required !! Default !! Description
|-
| platform || No || — || Platform name (NES, SNES, GBA) - adds platform-specific headers
|-
| region || No || — || Memory region name (Zero Page, Stack, Work RAM, VRAM, OAM, etc.)
|-
| description || No || (standard text) || Custom description for the page
|}

==Table Columns==

The generated table includes these columns:
* '''Address''' - Memory address (hex)
* '''Length''' - Size in bytes
* '''Type''' - Data type (byte, word, pointer, array, struct, etc.)
* '''Description''' - What the memory location stores

==Memory Regions by Platform==

===NES===
* $0000-$00ff: Zero Page (fast access)
* $0100-$01ff: Stack
* $0200-$07ff: Work RAM
* $2000-$2007: PPU Registers
* $4000-$4017: APU/IO Registers

===SNES===
* $0000-$1fff: Low RAM
* $7e0000-$7fffff: Work RAM
* $2100-$21ff: PPU Registers

==Example Output==

{{rammap|platform=NES|region=Zero Page}}

| $0010 || 1 || byte || Current game state
|-
| $0020 || 2 || word || Player X position
|-
|}

